<section xml:id="sec_tangent_lines">
  <title>Tangent Lines</title>
  <subsection>
    <title>Recommended Tutorials:</title>
    <p>
      Before starting on these exercises, you should familiarize yourself with material covered in the following tutorials:
      <ul>
        <li><xref ref="chp_assignment_operator" text="title" /></li>
        <li><xref ref="chp_equation_solvers" text="title" /></li>
        <li><xref ref="chp_derivative" text="title" /></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity, you will calculate tangent lines to functions, at various points and graph them along with the function. You 
      will also find points on a function where the tangent line has a specific slope.
    </p>
    <p>
      To find the tangent line to a function <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = a</m>, two pieces of information are needed:
      <ul>
        <li>The point, <m>(a, f(a))</m>.</li>
        <li>The slope of the tangent line, <m>f'(a)</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <aside>
      <p>
        A detailed example of finding and plotting tangent lines is described in <xref ref="subsec_equation_of_tangent_line"/>.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <p>
      Substituting these two pieces of information into the point-slope form of a line gives the following equation.
      <md>
        <mrow>y - y_0 \amp = m_{tan} \cdot (x-x_0) \nonumber</mrow>
        <mrow>y - f(a) \amp = f'(a) \cdot (x-a) \nonumber</mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_tanline" number="yes">y \amp = f'(a) \cdot (x-a) + f(a)</mrow>
      </md>
      <idx><h>lines</h><h>tangent line</h></idx>
      <idx><h>lines</h><h>slope of a tangent line</h></idx>
      You will need to use the resulting equation <xref ref="eq_tanline"/> in the following exercises.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <exercises>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Assign the function <m>f(x) = \sqrt{9 - x}</m> using the assignment operator <c>:=</c>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the equations of the tangent lines at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=5</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Be sure to assign different names for each tangent line, such as <c>line1</c> and <c>line2</c>. You will unique names 
            so that you can plot each line as well as <m>f(x)</m> in the next step.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Plot <m>f(x)</m> and the two tangent lines using a single <c>plot()</c> command.
            <idx><h>plot</h><h>multiple functions</h></idx>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Since you are plotting more than one tangent line on the same axes, it is a good idea to specify plot colours. An example 
            can be found in <xref ref="sec_plotting_multiple_functions"/>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Assign the function <m>g(x)=x{ e}^{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the equations of the tangent lines at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=-1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Make sure that you have properly defined your function using either <c>exp()</c> as the exponential function or using 
            the <m>e</m> from the palettes toolbar.
            <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential</h></idx>
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Plot <m>g(x)</m> and the two tangent lines using a single <c>plot()</c> command.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Assign the function <m>h(x)=x^3-x^2-9x+9</m>. In this exercise, you will need to solve for values of <m>x</m> where the 
          tangent line has a specified slope.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the <m>x</m>-values where the function has tangent lines with slope equal to <m>1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the <m>x</m>-values where the function has horizontal tangent lines.
            <idx><h>lines</h><h>horizontal tangent line</h></idx>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            You'll need to remember what the slope of a horizontal tangent line is to solve for <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>